parameter.detailed-description:
\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The mean observation time
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N at times $t_i$. The mean $\overline{t}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\overline{t} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N\ t_{i}.  {\label{eq:1}}
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The mean of the time series
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N. The mean $\overline{y}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\overline{y} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N\ y_{i}.  {\label{eq:1}}
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The mean error 
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N with error bars $\Delta y_i$. The mean $\overline{\Delta y}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\overline{\Delta y} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N\ \Delta y_{i}.  {\label{eq:1}}
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} weigthed mean
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The weighted mean $\overline{y}_{w}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\overline{y}_{w} = \frac{1}{W}\sum_{i=1}^N\ w_{i}\ y_{i}  {\label{eq:1}}
\end{equation}
where $W \equiv \sum_{i=1}^{N} w_{i}$ is the sum of the weights.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} median
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} The 50th percentile value, weighted or unweighted.

The general definition employed for weighted percentiles follows. Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $y_{(i)}$ be the derived sorted time series with $y_{(1)} \le y_{(2)} \le \cdots \le y_{(n)}$, with corresponding error bars $\Delta y_{(i)}$ and weights $w_{(i)}$. 
Note that $w_{(i)}$ is the corresponding weight of $y_{(i)}$, and not the $i$-th largest weight value. So it's \textbf{not} necessarily true that $w_{(1)} \le w_{(2)} \le \cdots \le w_{(N)}$.
The  $m$-th (per cent) weighted percentile $P_m$ is defined for $0<m\leq 100$ as follows:
\begin{equation}
P_m=\left\{ 
\begin{array}{ll}
y_{(1)} &  \mbox{if }  0< m< p_1 \\
y_{(i)}+\frac{m-p_i}{p_{i+1}-p_i}\,\left(y_{(i+1)}-y_{(i)}\right)& \mbox{if } p_i\leq m \leq p_{i+1}  \\
y_{(n)} &  \mbox{if }  p_n < m \leq 100
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
 p_i=\frac{100}{W'+1}\sum_{j=1}^i w'_{(j)}, ~~~W'=\sum_{k=1}^N w'_{(k)},~~~w'_{(k)}=\frac{w_{(k)}}{W}N, ~~~W=\sum_{k=1}^N w_{k}.
\end{equation}
This definition reduces to the result of the unweighted percentile of commons-math in the case of equal weights and it corresponds to the algorithm \texttt{type=6} of the \texttt{quantile} function of the \texttt{stats} package in \texttt{R}.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} median error
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} The 50th percentile of the errors, weighted or unweighted.

The general definition employed for weighted percentiles follows. Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $y_{(i)}$ be the derived sorted time series with $y_{(1)} \le y_{(2)} \le \cdots \le y_{(n)}$, with corresponding error bars $\Delta y_{(i)}$ and weights $w_{(i)}$. 
Note that $w_{(i)}$ is the corresponding weight of $y_{(i)}$, and not the $i$-th largest weight value. So it's \textbf{not} necessarily true that $w_{(1)} \le w_{(2)} \le \cdots \le w_{(N)}$.
The  $m$-th (per cent) weighted percentile $P_m$ is defined for $0<m\leq 100$ as follows:
\begin{equation}
P_m=\left\{ 
\begin{array}{ll}
y_{(1)} &  \mbox{if }  0< m< p_1 \\
y_{(i)}+\frac{m-p_i}{p_{i+1}-p_i}\,\left(y_{(i+1)}-y_{(i)}\right)& \mbox{if } p_i\leq m \leq p_{i+1}  \\
y_{(n)} &  \mbox{if }  p_n < m \leq 100
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
 p_i=\frac{100}{W'+1}\sum_{j=1}^i w'_{(j)}, ~~~W'=\sum_{k=1}^N w'_{(k)},~~~w'_{(k)}=\frac{w_{(k)}}{W}N, ~~~W=\sum_{k=1}^N w_{k}.
\end{equation}
This definition reduces to the result of the unweighted percentile of commons-math in the case of equal weights and it corresponds to the algorithm \texttt{type=6} of the \texttt{quantile} function of the \texttt{stats} package in \texttt{R}.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} Range
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series, $y_{\rm max}$ its largest element, and $y_{\rm min}$ its smallest element, then the range is defined as
\begin{equation}
R =  y_{\rm max} - y_{\rm min\label{eq:3}}
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The trimmed weighted mean
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} trim level $\alpha$ =5
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $Y_{\alpha}$ be the $\alpha$th weighted percentile, and $Y_{100-\alpha}$ be the $(100-\alpha)$th weighted percentile. Let $y'_{i}$ be the trimmed time series of size N' which is derived by iteratively removing the smallest or the largest values of the $y_{i}$ time series until 
$Y_{\alpha} < y'_{i} < Y_{100-\alpha}$ for all $i \in \{1,\cdots,N'\}$. The trimmed weighted mean is then defined as
\begin{equation}
\overline{y}' = \frac{1}{W'}\sum_{i=1}^{N'}\ w'_{i}\ y'_{i\label{eq:5}}
\end{equation}
where $W' \equiv \sum_{i=1}^{N'} w'_{i}$ is the sum of the trimmed weights $w'_{i}$ corresponding to $y'_{i}$.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The trimmed range
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} trim level $\alpha$ = 5
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $Y_{\alpha}$ be the $\alpha$th weighted percentile, and $Y_{100-\alpha}$ be the $(100-\alpha)$th weighted percentile. Let $y'_{i}$ be the trimmed time series of size N' which is derived by iteratively removing the smallest or the largest values of the $y_{i}$ time series until 
$Y_{\alpha} < y'_{i} < Y_{100-\alpha}$ for all $i \in \{1,\cdots,N'\}$. The trimmed range R' is defined as
\begin{equation}
R' = y'_{\rm max} - y'_{\rm min\label{eq:6}}
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\textbf{SELECT DESCRIPTION TO STAY IN JAN 2016 WHEN WE KNOW IF WE USE BIAS CORRECTED OR NOT (THE REFERENCE TO THE FLAG WILL BE REMOVED TOO)}
If the bias correction flag (in the field `SolutionIdScienceMetadata.isStatisticalParamBiasCorrected') is FALSE, the following definition applies:
\begin{description}
\item[] \textbf{Name:} The square root of the biased weighted variance around the weighted mean.
\item[] \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item[] \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i}$  [which might equal $(\Delta y_{i})^{-2}$]. The weighted standard deviation $\hat{\sigma}_{w}$ is defined as the square root of the sample-size biased weighted variance:
\[
\hat{\sigma}_{w} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{W}\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_i (y_i-\overline{y}_w)^2}
\]
where $W=\sum_{i=1}^N w_i$ and  $\overline{y}_{w}$ is the weighted mean. \\
\end{description}

If the bias correction flag (in the field `SolutionIdScienceMetadata.isStatisticalParamBiasCorrected') is TRUE, the following definition applies:
\begin{description}
\item[] \textbf{Name:} The square root of the unbiased weighted variance around the weighted mean.
\item[] \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0 with size $N > 1$.
\item[] \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i}$  [which might equal $(\Delta y_{i})^{-2}$]. The weighted standard deviation $\hat{\sigma}_{w}$ is defined as the square root of the sample-size unbiased weighted variance:
\[
\hat{\sigma}_{w} = \sqrt{\frac{V_1}{V_1^2-V_2}\sum_{i=1}^{N}w_i (y_i-\overline{y}_w)^2}
\]
where $V_p=\sum_{i=1}^N w_i^p$ and  $\overline{y}_{w}$ is the weighted mean. 
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} Confidence interval for the weighted mean
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} the confidence level $\alpha \in ]0,1[$
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The two-sided $100 (1-\alpha)\%$ confidence interval of the weighted mean $\overline{y}_{w}$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\overline{y}_{w} \pm t_{1-\alpha/2, N-1} \ \frac{\hat{\sigma}_{w}}{\sqrt{W}\label{eq:8}}
\end{equation}
where $W \equiv \sum_{i=1}^{N} w_{i}$ is the sum of the weights, $\hat{\sigma}_{w}$ is the weighted standard deviation around the weighted mean, and $t_{1-\alpha/2, N-1}$ is the $(1-\alpha/2)$ percentile of the \textbf{t} distribution with $N-1$ degrees of freedom.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The weighted normalized point-to-point scatter
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The weighted normalized point-to-point scatter $S_{pp}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
S_{pp} = \frac{1}{\hat{\sigma}_{w}^{2} \ W} \ \sum_{i=2}^{N} \frac{(y_{i} - y_{i-1})^{2}}{w_{i}^{-1} + w_{i-1}^{-1}\label{eq:12}}
\end{equation}
where $W \equiv \sum_{i=1}^{N} w_{i}$ is the sum of the weights, and $\hat{\sigma}_{w}$ is the weighted standard deviation around the weighted mean.
If $\hat{\sigma}^2_w$ is not positive, the default value of one is returned (consistent with the expected result of a constant star).
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Median Absolute Deviation (MAD)
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N. The MAD is defined as the median of the absolute deviations from the median of the data:
\begin{equation}
\mbox{MAD}=\mbox{median}\{|y_i-\mbox{median}\{y_j, \forall j\in(1,N)\} |, \forall i\in(1,N) \}.
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The $\chi^2$ value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The $\chi^2$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N\ \frac{(y_{i}-\overline{y}_{w})^2}{\Delta y_{i}^2}=
\sum_{i=1}^N \left(\frac{y_i}{\Delta y_{i}}\right)^2-\frac{\left[\sum_{i=1}^N y_i/(\Delta y_{i})^2\right]^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (1/\Delta y_{i})^2}
\end{equation}
where $\overline{y}_{w}$ is the weighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Abbe value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $\{t_i,y_{i}\}$ be a time-sorted time series of size $N$, such that $t_i<t_{i+1}$ for all $i<N$. The Abbe value $\cal{A}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
{\cal A}=\frac{N}{2(N-1)}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N-1} (y_{i+1}-y_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (y_i-\bar{y})}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{y}$ is the unweighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Abbe value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $\{t_i,y_{i}\}$ be a time-sorted time series of size $N$, such that $t_i<t_{i+1}$ for all $i<N$. The Abbe value $\cal{A}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
{\cal A}=\frac{N}{2(N-1)}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N-1} (y_{i+1}-y_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (y_i-\bar{y})}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{y}$ is the unweighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Interquartile Range (IQR)
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} The difference between the 75th and 25th (weighted or unweighted) percentile values: IQR$=P_{75}-P_{25}$.

The general definition employed for weighted percentiles follows. Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $y_{(i)}$ be the derived sorted time series with $y_{(1)} \le y_{(2)} \le \cdots \le y_{(n)}$, with corresponding error bars $\Delta y_{(i)}$ and weights $w_{(i)}$. 
Note that $w_{(i)}$ is the corresponding weight of $y_{(i)}$, and not the $i$-th largest weight value. So it's \textbf{not} necessarily true that $w_{(1)} \le w_{(2)} \le \cdots \le w_{(N)}$.
The  $m$-th (per cent) weighted percentile $P_m$ is defined for $0<m\leq 100$ as follows:
\begin{equation}
P_m=\left\{ 
\begin{array}{ll}
y_{(1)} &  \mbox{if }  0< m< p_1 \\
y_{(i)}+\frac{m-p_i}{p_{i+1}-p_i}\,\left(y_{(i+1)}-y_{(i)}\right)& \mbox{if } p_i\leq m \leq p_{i+1}  \\
y_{(n)} &  \mbox{if }  p_n < m \leq 100
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
 p_i=\frac{100}{W'+1}\sum_{j=1}^i w'_{(j)}, ~~~W'=\sum_{k=1}^N w'_{(k)},~~~w'_{(k)}=\frac{w_{(k)}}{W}N, ~~~W=\sum_{k=1}^N w_{k}.
\end{equation}
This definition reduces to the result of the unweighted percentile of commons-math in the case of equal weights and it corresponds to the algorithm \texttt{type=6} of the \texttt{quantile} function of the \texttt{stats} package in \texttt{R}.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The most outlying measurement with respect to the median
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The most outlying measurement is defined as the greatest absolute deviation from the median normalized by the error:
\begin{equation}
\mbox{outlierMedian} = \max \left\{\frac{ |y_i-\mbox{median}\{y_j, \forall j\in (1,N) \}|} {\Delta y_i}, \forall i\in (1,N) \right\}.
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The signal-to-noise estimate
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The signal-to-noise ratio (S/N) is estimated as
\begin{equation}
\mbox{S/N} = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^N\ (y_i-\overline{y})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N\ \Delta y_{i}^2 } }
\end{equation}
where $\overline{y}$ is the mean of the time-series values.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The $\chi^2$ criterion for variability
\item \textbf{Input:} A time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements with errors
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The weighted $\chi^2$ test statistic is given by
\begin{equation}
\chi^2={\sum w_i \sum y_i^2w_i - (\sum y_iw_i)^2 \over \sum w_i}
\end{equation}

The number of degrees of freedom is given by  $\nu=N$. The reduced $\chi^2$ is obtined by dividing the $\chi^2$ test statistic by $\nu$.

The $rvConstancyProbability$ is the p-value for variability, defined as the probability that the observed $\chi^2$ will exceed the expected value from a $\chi^2$ distribution with significance level $\alpha$. It is a continuous probability [0,1] where 1== very strong probability of constancy, 0 == very low probability of constancy.

The p-value  can be computed in Java as

\begin{equation}
ChiSquaredDistribution distribution = \\
            new ChiSquaredDistribution(N - 1.0);
double rvConstancyProbability = 1.0 - distribution.cumulativeProbability(\chi^2);
\end{equation}
\end{description}

Flag indicating if variability was identified in the photometric G band:

\begin{itemize}
\item["NOT_AVAILABLE" =] source not processed and/or exported to catalogue
\item["CONSTANT" =] Source not identified as variable
\item["VARIABLE" =] source identified and processed as variable, see tables PhotVariableSummary and PhotVariableTimeSeriesGfov for more details.
\end{itemize}

this parameter is filled with the probability to belong to a Cepheid's type. The parameter type is double[3].
cepheidtypeClassification[0] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the DCEP type;
cepheidtypeClassification[1] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the T2CEP type; cepheidtypeClassification[2] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the ACEP type.

this parameter is filled with the probability to belong to a T2CEP subtype. The parameter type is double[3].
cepheidType2SubClassification[0] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the BL Her type; 
cepheidtypeClassification[1] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the W Vir type;
cepheidtypeClassification[2] corresponds to the probability of belonging to the RV Tau type.

This parameter is filled with the probability that a Cepheid pulsates in a given mode.
The parameter type is a double[3]. 
cepheidModeClassification[0] corresponds to the probability to pulsate in the fundamental mode; 
cepheidModeClassification[1] corresponds to the probability to pulsate in the first overtone mode; 
cepheidModeClassification[2] corresponds to the probability to pulsate in the second overtone pulsation mode.

Number of identified fundamental frequencies in the photometric G band:

\begin{itemize}
\item[0 =] NOT PERIODIC
\item[1 =] MONO-PERIODIC
\item[$>1$ =] MULTI-PERIODIC
\end{itemize}

Photometric variability classification for a limited set of types processed for this catalogue: \\\textbf{[UPDATE DESCRIPTION IN JAN 2016 TO REFLECT ACTUALLY EXPORTED TYPES]}
\begin{itemize}
\item[`' =] No classification available,\newline i.e., source is not variable, or not processed and/or exported to catalogue.
\item[`CEPHEID' =] Variable of the Cepheid type, see table \textit{Cepheid} for source details.
\item[`RRL' =] Variable of the RR Lyrae type, see table \textit{RRLyrae} for source details.
\item[`SHORT-TIMESCALE' =] Variable with short-timescale variability, see table \textit{ShortTimeScale} for source details.
\item[`MICROLENS' =] Microlensing event, see table \textit{Microlensing} for source details.
\end{itemize}

For classification of Cepheids and RR Lyrea, the tables `Cepheid' and `RRLyrae' contain detailed results, respectively.

