\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N. The MAD is defined as the median of the absolute deviations from the median of the data:
\begin{equation}
\mbox{MAD}=\mbox{median}\{|y_i-\mbox{median}\{y_j, \forall j\in(1,N)\} |, \forall i\in(1,N) \}.
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The $\chi^2$ value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The $\chi^2$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N\ \frac{(y_{i}-\overline{y}_{w})^2}{\Delta y_{i}^2}=
\sum_{i=1}^N \left(\frac{y_i}{\Delta y_{i}}\right)^2-\frac{\left[\sum_{i=1}^N y_i/(\Delta y_{i})^2\right]^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (1/\Delta y_{i})^2}
\end{equation}
where $\overline{y}_{w}$ is the weighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Abbe value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $\{t_i,y_{i}\}$ be a time-sorted time series of size $N$, such that $t_i<t_{i+1}$ for all $i<N$. The Abbe value $\cal{A}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
{\cal A}=\frac{N}{2(N-1)}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N-1} (y_{i+1}-y_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (y_i-\bar{y})}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{y}$ is the unweighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Abbe value
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $\{t_i,y_{i}\}$ be a time-sorted time series of size $N$, such that $t_i<t_{i+1}$ for all $i<N$. The Abbe value $\cal{A}$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
{\cal A}=\frac{N}{2(N-1)}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N-1} (y_{i+1}-y_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N (y_i-\bar{y})}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{y}$ is the unweighted mean.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The Interquartile Range (IQR)
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} The difference between the 75th and 25th (weighted or unweighted) percentile values: IQR$=P_{75}-P_{25}$.

The general definition employed for weighted percentiles follows. Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. Let $y_{(i)}$ be the derived sorted time series with $y_{(1)} \le y_{(2)} \le \cdots \le y_{(n)}$, with corresponding error bars $\Delta y_{(i)}$ and weights $w_{(i)}$. 
Note that $w_{(i)}$ is the corresponding weight of $y_{(i)}$, and not the $i$-th largest weight value. So it's \textbf{not} necessarily true that $w_{(1)} \le w_{(2)} \le \cdots \le w_{(N)}$.
The  $m$-th (per cent) weighted percentile $P_m$ is defined for $0<m\leq 100$ as follows:
\begin{equation}
P_m=\left\{ 
\begin{array}{ll}
y_{(1)} &  \mbox{if }  0< m< p_1 \\
y_{(i)}+\frac{m-p_i}{p_{i+1}-p_i}\,\left(y_{(i+1)}-y_{(i)}\right)& \mbox{if } p_i\leq m \leq p_{i+1}  \\
y_{(n)} &  \mbox{if }  p_n < m \leq 100
\end{array}
\right. 
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
 p_i=\frac{100}{W'+1}\sum_{j=1}^i w'_{(j)}, ~~~W'=\sum_{k=1}^N w'_{(k)},~~~w'_{(k)}=\frac{w_{(k)}}{W}N, ~~~W=\sum_{k=1}^N w_{k}.
\end{equation}
This definition reduces to the result of the unweighted percentile of commons-math in the case of equal weights and it corresponds to the algorithm \texttt{type=6} of the \texttt{quantile} function of the \texttt{stats} package in \texttt{R}.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The most outlying measurement with respect to the median
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The most outlying measurement is defined as the greatest absolute deviation from the median normalized by the error:
\begin{equation}
\mbox{outlierMedian} = \max \left\{\frac{ |y_i-\mbox{median}\{y_j, \forall j\in (1,N) \}|} {\Delta y_i}, \forall i\in (1,N) \right\}.
\end{equation}
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The signal-to-noise estimate
\item \textbf{Input:} Gaia time series containing only observations with CU7 reject flag=0.
\item \textbf{Control parameters:} None
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of size N, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$. The signal-to-noise ratio (S/N) is estimated as
\begin{equation}
\mbox{S/N} = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^N\ (y_i-\overline{y})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N\ \Delta y_{i}^2 } }
\end{equation}
where $\overline{y}$ is the mean of the time-series values.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The $\chi^2$ criterion for variability
\item \textbf{Input:} A time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements with errors
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The weighted $\chi^2$ test statistic is given by
\begin{equation}
\chi^2={\sum w_i \sum y_i^2w_i - (\sum y_iw_i)^2 \over \sum w_i}
\end{equation}

The number of degrees of freedom is given by  $\nu=N$. The reduced $\chi^2$ is obtined by dividing the $\chi^2$ test statistic by $\nu$.

The $rvConstancyProbability$ is the p-value for variability, defined as the probability that the observed $\chi^2$ will exceed the expected value from a $\chi^2$ distribution with significance level $\alpha$. It is a continuous probability [0,1] where 1== very strong probability of constancy, 0 == very low probability of constancy.

The p-value  can be computed in Java as

\begin{equation}
ChiSquaredDistribution distribution = \\
            new ChiSquaredDistribution(N - 1.0);
double rvConstancyProbability = 1.0 - distribution.cumulativeProbability(\chi^2);
\end{equation}
\end{description}

Flag indicating if variability was identified in the photometric G band:

\begin{itemize}
\item["NOT_AVAILABLE" =] source not processed and/or exported to catalogue
\item["CONSTANT" =] Source not identified as variable
\item["VARIABLE" =] source identified and processed as variable, see tables PhotVariableSummary and PhotVariableTimeSeriesGfov for more details.
\end{itemize}

Contamination and confusion flag. \\
Four character string, one character per band [W1/W2/W3/W4], that indicates that the photometry and/or position measurements of a source may be contaminated or biased due to proximity to an image artifact. \\
The type of artifact that may contaminate the measurements is denoted by the following codes. Lower-case letters correspond to instances in which the source detection in a band is believed to be real but the measurement may be contaminated by the artifact. Upper-case letters are instances in which the source detection in a band may be a spurious detection of an artifact.
\begin{itemize}
\item{D,d - Diffraction spike. Source may be a spurious detection of (D) or contaminated by (d) a diffraction spike from a nearby bright star on the same image, or}
\item{P,p - Persistence. Source may be a spurious detection of (P) or contaminated by (p) a short-term latent image left by a bright source, or}
\item{H,h - Halo. Source may be a spurious detection of (H) or contaminated by (h) the scattered light halo surrounding a nearby bright source, or}
\item{O,o (letter "o") - Optical ghost. Source may be a spurious detection of (O) or contaminated by (o) an optical ghost image caused by a nearby bright source, or}
\item{0 (number zero) - Source is unaffected by known artifacts.}
\end{itemize}
A source extraction may be affected by more than one type of artifact or condition. In this event, the ccFlags value in each band is set in the following priority order: D,P,H,O,d,p,h,o,0. \\
A source can appear in the AllWISE Source Catalog even if it is flagged as a spurious artifact detection in a band if there is a reliable detection in another band that is not flagged as a spurious artifact detection.\\
CAUTION: Non-zero ccFlags values in any band indicate the the measurement in that band may be contaminated and the photometry should be used with caution.\\

Extended source flag.\\ 
This is an integer flag, the value of which indicates whether or not the morphology of a source is consistent with the WISE point spread function in any band, or whether the source is associated with or superimposed on a previously known extended object from the 2MASS Extended Source Catalog (XSC). \\
The values of the extFlag indicate the following conditions:
\begin{itemize}
\item{0 - The source shape is consistent with a point-source and the source is not associated with or superimposed on a 2MASS XSC source}
\item{1 - The profile-fit photometry goodness-of-fit is $>$3.0 in one or more bands.}
\item{2 - The source falls within the extrapolated isophotal footprint of a 2MASS XSC source.}
\item{3 - The profile-fit photometry goodness-of-fit is $>$3.0 in one or more bands, and the source falls within the extrapolated isophotal footprint of a 2MASS XSC source.}
\item{4 - The source position falls within 5 arcsec of a 2MASS XSC source.}
\item{5 - The profile-fit photometry goodness-of-fit is $>$3.0 in one or more bands, and the source position falls within 5 arcsec of a 2MASS XSC source.}
\end{itemize}
CAUTION: WISE profile-fit (w?mpro) measurements are optimized for point sources and will systematically underestimate the true flux of resolved objects. If a source entry has extFlag$>$0, you may wish to examine the elliptical aperture photometry which are measured using areas that are scaled from 2MASS XSC morphologies.

Photometric quality flag. \\
Four character flag, one character per band [W1/W2/W3/W4], that provides a shorthand summary of the quality of the profile-fit photometry measurement in each band, as derived from the measurement signal-to-noise ratio.
\begin{itemize}
\item{A - Source is detected in this band with a flux signal-to-noise ratio $>$10.}
\item{B - Source is detected in this band with a flux signal-to-noise ratio 3$<snr<$10.}
\item{C - Source is detected in this band with a flux signal-to-noise ratio 2$<snr<$3.}
\item{U - Upper limit on magnitude. Source measurement has w?snr$<$2. The profile-fit magnitude w?mpro is a 95\% confidence upper limit.}
\item{X - A profile-fit measurement was not possible at this location in this band. The value of w?mpro and w?sigmpro will be "null" in this band.}
\item{Z - A profile-fit source flux measurement was made at this location, but the flux uncertainty could not be measured. The value of w?sigmpro will be "null" in this band. The value of w?mpro will be "null" if the measured flux, w?flux, is negative, but will not be "null" if the flux is positive. If a non-null magnitude is present, it corresponds to the true flux, and not the 95\% confidence upper limit. This occurs for a small number of sources found in a narrow range of ecliptic longitude which were covered by a large number of saturated pixels from 3-Band Cryo single-exposures.}
\end{itemize}

Contamination and confusion flag. \\
Four character string, one character per band [W1/W2/W3/W4], that indicates that the photometry and/or position measurements of a source may be contaminated or biased due to proximity to an image artifact. \\
The type of artifact that may contaminate the measurements is denoted by the following codes. Lower-case letters correspond to instances in which the source detection in a band is believed to be real but the measurement may be contaminated by the artifact. Upper-case letters are instances in which the source detection in a band may be a spurious detection of an artifact.
\begin{itemize}
\item{D,d - Diffraction spike. Source may be a spurious detection of (D) or contaminated by (d) a diffraction spike from a nearby bright star on the same image, or}
\item{P,p - Persistence. Source may be a spurious detection of (P) or contaminated by (p) a short-term latent image left by a bright source, or}
