Reference to the Variability Annex.\\
\begin{itemize}
\item{0 = no reference in any of the variability annexes}
\item{1 = reference to the Variability Annex: Periodic variables}
\item{2 = reference to the Variability Annex: Unsolved variables}
\end{itemize}

Reference to the Variability Annex.\\
\begin{itemize}
\item{0 = no reference in any of the variability annexes}
\item{1 = reference to the Variability Annex: Periodic variables}
\item{2 = reference to the Variability Annex: Unsolved variables}
\end{itemize}

Photometric quality flag. Three character flag, one character per band [JHKs], that provides a summary of the net quality of the default photometry in each band.\\
The value for ph\_qual is set for a band according to the precedence of the table below. For example, a source that is tested and meets the conditions for category "X" is not tested for subsequent qualities.
\begin{itemize}
\item{"X" - There is a detection at this location, but no valid brightness estimate can be extracted using any algorithm. Default magnitude is null.}
\item{"U" - Upper limit on magnitude. Source is not detected in this band, or it is detected, but not resolved in a consistent fashion with other bands. A value of ph\_qual="U" does not necessarily mean that there is no flux detected in this band at the location. }
\item{"F" - This category includes sources where a reliable estimate of the photometric error could not be determined. The uncertainties reported for these sources in [jhk]\_msigcom are flags and have numeric values $>$8.0.}
\item{"E" - This category includes detections where the goodness-of-fit quality of the profile-fit photometry was very poor, or detections where psf fit photometry did not converge and an aperture magnitude is reported, or detections where the number of frames was too small in relation to the number of frames in which a detection was geometrically possible.}
\item{"A" - Detections in any brightness regime where valid measurements were made with [jhk]\_snr$>$10 AND [jhk]\_cmsig$<$0.10857.}
\item{"B" - Detections in any brightness regime where valid measurements were made  with [jhk]\_snr$>$7 AND [jhk]\_cmsig$<$0.15510.}
\item{"C" - Detections in any brightness regime where valid measurements were made with [jhk]\_snr$>$5 AND [jhk]\_cmsig$<$0.21714.}
\item{"D" - Detections in any brightness regime where valid measurements were made with no [jhk]\_snr or [jhk]\_cmsig requirement.}
\end{itemize}

The {\bf cdf} flag is a combined double star flag used to indicate the type/quality of double star fit. It is a combination of 2 flags:
{\bf cdf = $(10 \cdot dsf) + dst$ }
where
{\bf dsf} = double star flag = overall classification \begin{itemize} \item 0 = single star \item 1 = component \#1 of "good" double star \item 2 = component \#2 of "good" double star \item 3 = blended image \end{itemize}
{\bf dst} = double star type, from pixel data image profile fits, largest value of all images used for this star \begin{itemize} \item 0 = no double star, not sufficient \#pixels or elongation \item to even call double star fit subroutine \item 1 = elongated image but no more than 1 peak detected \item 2 = 2 separate peaks detected $\to$ try double star fit \item 3 = secondary peak found on each side of primary \item 4 = case 1 after successful double fit (small separ. blended image) \item 5 = case 2 after successful double fit (most likely real double) \item 6 = case 3 after successful double fit (brighter secondary picked) \end{itemize}
{\bf Caution}: often a dsf= 1 or 2 image is paired with a dsf= 3. If for a star any of the several images reveals a "blended image", that higher dsf=3 flag is carried into the output file. This can happen for a regular double star with unique components 1 and 2. A flag dsf=3 means this could be component 1 or 2 but at least on one CCD frame a blended image was detected. This blend could be with the other component, or a spurious image or artifact. The double star flags need to be interpreted with caution; anything but a zero means "likely some double star component or blended image".

The {\bf cdf} flag is a combined double star flag used to indicate the type/quality of double star fit. It is a combination of 2 flags:
{\bf cdf = $(10 \cdot dsf) + dst$ }
where
{\bf dsf} = double star flag = overall classification \begin{itemize} \item 0 = single star \item 1 = component \#1 of "good" double star \item 2 = component \#2 of "good" double star \item 3 = blended image \end{itemize}
{\bf dst} = double star type, from pixel data image profile fits, largest value of all images used for this star \begin{itemize} \item 0 = no double star, not sufficient \#pixels or elongation \item to even call double star fit subroutine \item 1 = elongated image but no more than 1 peak detected \item 2 = 2 separate peaks detected $\to$ try double star fit \item 3 = secondary peak found on each side of primary \item 4 = case 1 after successful double fit (small separ. blended image) \item 5 = case 2 after successful double fit (most likely real double) \item 6 = case 3 after successful double fit (brighter secondary picked) \end{itemize}
{\bf Caution}: often a dsf= 1 or 2 image is paired with a dsf= 3. If for a star any of the several images reveals a "blended image", that higher dsf=3 flag is carried into the output file. This can happen for a regular double star with unique components 1 and 2. A flag dsf=3 means this could be component 1 or 2 but at least on one CCD frame a blended image was detected. This blend could be with the other component, or a spurious image or artifact. The double star flags need to be interpreted with caution; anything but a zero means "likely some double star component or blended image".

table.description:
This datamodel describes Gaia input to the cross-match algorithm. This is not the original CatalogueSource, 
but is the working copy of Gaia to be used for the cross-match. \\
{\bf GaiaBaseCat should not be PUBLIC.}

parameter.detailed-description:
\begin{description}
\item \textbf{Name:} The $\chi^2$ criterion for variability
\item \textbf{Input:} A time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements with errors
\item \textbf{Output:} Let $y_{i}$ be a time series of STA Radial Velocity measurements of size $N$, with error bars $\Delta y_{i}$ and weights $w_{i} \equiv 1/(\Delta y_{i})^{2}$. The weighted $\chi^2$ test statistic is given by
\begin{equation}
\chi^2={\sum w_i \sum y_i^2w_i - (\sum y_iw_i)^2 \over \sum w_i}
\end{equation}

The number of degrees of freedom is given by  $\nu=N$. The reduced $\chi^2$ is obtined by dividing the $\chi^2$ test statistic by $\nu$.

The $rvConstancyProbability$ is the p-value for variability, defined as the probability that the observed $\chi^2$ will exceed the expected value from a $\chi^2$ distribution with significance level $\alpha$. It is a continuous probability [0,1] where 1== very strong probability of constancy, 0 == very low probability of constancy.

The p-value  can be computed in Java as

\begin{equation}
ChiSquaredDistribution distribution = \\
            new ChiSquaredDistribution(N - 1.0);
double rvConstancyProbability = 1.0 - distribution.cumulativeProbability(\chi^2);
\end{equation}
\end{description}

Flag indicating if variability was identified in the photometric G band:

\begin{itemize}
\item["NOT_AVAILABLE" =] source not processed and/or exported to catalogue
\item["CONSTANT" =] Source not identified as variable
\item["VARIABLE" =] source identified and processed as variable, see tables PhotVariableSummary and PhotVariableTimeSeriesGfov for more details.
\end{itemize}

The color of the particle encoded in RGBA. This follows Java specifications.

\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Alpha} : bits 24 to 31. Omission means full opacity.
\item {\bf Red} : bits 16 to 23;
\item {\bf Green} :  bits 8 to 15;
\item {\bf Blue} : bits 0 to 7.
\end{itemize}
